ratings.question_text: Your level of engagement with the course was:
What is your overall assessment of this course?
The course was well organized to facilitate student learning.
I received clear feedback that improved my learning.
Relative to other courses you have taken at Yale, the level of intellectual challenge of this course was:
Relative to other courses you have taken at Yale, the workload of this course was:

narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: This class was great and very well taught. I learned a lot of tangible analysis methods in statistics.

My understanding of statistics improved so much, and everything we learned was so applied. I now feel very confident using SPSS for data analysis, writing up statistical findings according to APA formatting.
SPSS, statistical write-ups, hypothesis testing

Skills in the statistical analysis program SPSS, knowledge of writing up statistical results in APA format for psychology research, application of statistical analysis to data for answering testing psychological hypotheses
I learned basics of statistics that I didn't remember from high school. Also SPSS.
I learned the basics of statistical analysis and how to evaluate statistical claims in SPSS. I also learned how to write up a research report.
I learned basic stats and SPSS.
I learned how to conduct multiple statistical tests as well as the concepts behind them.
A quantitative and qualitative understanding of Statistics, technological literacy with programs such as SPSS, deep knowledge of statistical tests and their various applications.
Learned about different statistical tests to test hypotheses such as one-way anovas, two-way anovas, independent samples t-tests, and more.
I learned about multiple statistical analyses and when to apply them as well as the foundational principles of statistics.
APA formatting, basic statistical tests and analysis, and application of statistics to psychological studies.
Statistical analysis for psychology research
SPSS
I gained an even stronger understanding of core statistical concepts, and I developed an especially greater understanding of how to apply these concepts to psychological research.
General knowledge about stats!
How to use SPSS and its application to psychology.
You learned a pretty basic, but thorough intro to statistics. We stopped at ANOVA tests, and we learned how to use SPS

I learned how to use SPSS statistics programs, how to conduct base level statistical tests and analyze them in a comprehensive report. I learned how to test the significance of the data and how to determine when to use which test.

I learned how to use SPSS! Super helpful skill for my future. I fell in love with stats with this course. I learned how to write statistical results in APA format. Overall: extremely helpful course, and I am so happy I took it.
This class represented practical statistical techniques and challenged my use of the software SPSS.
Learning how to use SPSS, and analyse data in a research paper

Through this course, I learned to run and visualize statistical tests in SPSS, which overall allowed me to make better sense of data. I enjoyed learning about when to use specific tests and how to use them, as well as thinking about limitations of studies beyond merely sample size issues.
I learned how to run statistical tests on SPSS, make statistical claims based on those results and how to think critically about those results.
I learnt how to carry out t-tests, ANOVA tests and z-tests. I also improved my statstical sceptism in the greater world.
Basic statistical skills will allow you to conduct research tests and analyze the data effectively, particularly in the social sciences.
I learned how to do statistical testing using SPSS
Professor Gee is the best Professor I have yet to meet. She loves her work, loves her student and that translates effectively to the engagement and success of the class

I knew very little about statistics before this course, and learned a lot. I feel comfortable using SPSS, and if somebody handed me the results section of a psychology paper I could probably tell you what it means!
I learned what is statistics. Ive learned how to do data analysis and how to apply my knowledge to real life data

I learned the fundamentals of SPSS and how to use statistics to analyze and evaluate data. I have gained knowledge on how to select and run statistical tests, interpreting results, and understanding the significance behind my findings. This course has also given me insight into real-world applications of statistics and data analysis especially in the psychological research context.

Prof Gee makes a tremendous effort to set all of the information she teaches within a relevant context to most of her students. For the most part, she introduces statistical concepts as they pertain to social science or similar research, which is very helpful as a psychology student. I learned how to run a series of different statistical tests using SPSS, which is also a very relevant program. In addition to this, this course also taught me a lot about how to effectively type up my statistical results using APA format.
I learned about how to use SPSS and basic statistics knowledge.
I learned how to use SPSS and make my own research project.

I certainly have a better grasp over statistical tests and the power of using statistics to understand the world around me. I found this course to be incredibly fascinating, particularly learning about statistics from a lens of psychology and mental health.
use of SPSS, analyzing and reporting data in APA format
I learned more about how statistics can apply to many different subjects. I also learned how to be more aware of biases in how statistical data is presented in the media.
I developed time management skills and also learned how to use SPSS.
spss, intro stats, correlation models

I learned how to use statistics in the real world, especially within the field of psychology. I learned how data is taken within psychology studies, and how that data is analyzed to come to certain conclusions.
I (kind of) learned how to use SPSS. I learned about ANOVA tests, which was something I did not know from AP Stats.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Strengths are definitely the lectures being super informative, lecture slides being very thorough. A weakness is having both a final and a final project.

The class was very applied and the section and lecture went very well together. Everything we did felt super relevant for real world applications. The main weakness might just be that lecture sometimes moved very fast.

Stregths: GREAT QR! Interesting, applied... You work with real-world Data in HWs and use statistical software to do the math. The focus is on applied data, not tedious things like numbers. Again, TAKE THIS AS YOUR QR if you're humanities! Dr. Gee releases the midterm/exam questions 24 hours in advance so you can process it (great for people with test anxiety) and chooses engaging assignments.
Strengths: very(!) well-organized, homework, lectures, exams, and final projects all fit well together. A perfectly taught course. Amazing.
The only weakness of this course is that it teaches SPSS, and this only applies if you need to take a course in the future that will need R.

Professor Gee was a huge asset to this course. She was an incredibly engaging and kind professor, always open to any questions. The TFs were a weakness. They were not very knowledgable in the course material and would at times give conflicting information.
The class was comprehensive and focused a lot on real-world applications. However, the concepts we learned in the final few weeks of class seemed a bit rushed.
The strengths of this course are the weekly assignments and labs that always closely followed what we learned in class and taught us how to apply the information.

Strengths of the course include interesting course material, straightforward lecture style, and accessible material that was easy to practice. Weaknesses of the course include tedious lab sections and overly-accessible lectures (to the point where lecture attendance no longer became compulsory).
Strengths included the organization of the class and structure of the course.

The class was great! The lecture was well-paced, Prof. Gee explained all the concepts and tests so as to make learning easy, and the homeworks and sections truly reflected what we were expected to learn.

Very manageable course load, opportunities to improve and receive feedback, varied homework assignments that expose students to research in psych field. Could be confusing without the use of the lab guides.

I liked that it wasn't just your typical stats class. Prof. Gee makes sure to include real-life applications of all of our statistical analysis> There is help available through EdThreads and so much support from the TFs.
Weekly psets and sections did a good job recapping the topics taught in class.
I thought it was great

The course was exceptionally structured and organized. Communication between Professor Gee and the TFs was very clear and timely, and the lab section materials were especially helpful. Homeworks were posted promptly and feedback was very clear. Also, we were very well prepared for the final project and grading was also very quick.
This is a wonderful course -- you are provided with a broad overview of stats and great steps are taken to ensure student comprehension. Take this as a QR!!
Very engaging and well organized.

this course was well organized, each grading and canvas posting submission was on time. the TFs grading comments were very helpful on homework assignments. the lectures were easy to follow, and the labs were extremely helpful in reviewing what we learned in class. i wish this class did not have both a final in class exam and a final project. i believe assigning two large items at the end of the semester was very stressful for students. i would have preferred one midterm exam and then either one final exam or one final project. the structure of these assignments were very similar so it felt repetitive.

Strengths: the instructor! Dr. Gee is super engaging one-on-one. Well-organized course. Slides were clear. Receptive to student feedback. Instructions were super clear, and when they weren't, were changed. Awesome!! Lectures were recorded as well, which was lovely. While I only used them for when I was sick/had an overlapping interview, overall was good.
Weaknesses: No office hours on the weekends (I was unable to go to any office hours during the semester because they always coincided with a class. I think if I went to office hours, I would not have gotten nearly as many unnecessary points off on homework as I did this semester)
The lectures were relatively engaging. I enjoyed seeing the psychological applications of statistics. I also felt like I knew my TA well and grew closer to her throughout the course of the semester.
The labs were the most helpful

One strength of this course was how lab sections helped me better understand what we went over in lectureI felt that after lab I was more confident in running tests and being able to explain what they mean. The availability of materials on Canvas (lab keys, lecture slides, etc.) was also super helpful! One thing that could be improved is the speed at which lectures were conductedalthough I eventually felt like I had a stronger grasp on the material, sometimes I felt that lecture went too fast.
Loved this class! Prof Gee is a really good instructor and made the class really engaging

Strengths:
-The exams really built on the homeworks and labs so were straightforward to study for

Weaknesses: 
- Prof Gee spent a lot of time on course announcements and such which was a complete waste of lecture time and could have been in an email. This sometimes took up 10 minutes or more. 
- The first few lectures could have been compressed into one prerequisite - material like the mean, mode and median should not be being taught at college - it was necessary so could have been required previewing

This class was so well organized and provided so many opportunities for practice and for you to understand the material. The labs were incredibly helpful for filling in any gaps or confusion in the lecture and was very hands-on. The structure of the exams was perfect and allowed me to focus on conducting the tests and interpreting the data rather than frantically writing. Love Professor Gee!
Strength: Professor Gee, class organization, everything was perfect and tailored to help us succeed

Prof. Gee cares deeply about her students and is so patient and kind. I enjoyed the format of the course, especially the final project at the end. The lab sections sometimes felt a bit dry (this is where we learn how to use SPSS), but as the course went on they began to feel more related to what we were learning about in lecture, which made them more enjoyable.
Strength: very good pace; labs add on to lecture material.

The course lectures are well-structured. Each lecture centers around a specific statistical concept and each concept logically builds upon the previous one. The teacher's approach to presenting topics is highly effective. Her practice of defining the concept followed by providing examples helps solidify and enhance my understanding of the concept. The lab sections with their practical application and hands-on experience working with SPSS have been particularly helpful for me to learn how to execute what we have learned in class.
No weaknesses! This course is great for anyone studying social science or who wants to see a practical relevant application of statistics.
I think the lectures were a good pace and it was easy to follow.

The lectures at the beginning were very simple compared to the rest of the year. Things like mean and mode were explained in the beginning which are things taught back in elementary and middle school.

I really liked the format of having weekly homework assignments and sections. Having consistent practice running statistical tests absolutely facilitated my learning and understanding. I wish sections were more collaborative though.
good slideshows, more time spent learning correct APA formatting
The lecture slides were detailed and had helpful examples for different statistical tests. The feedback on the homework assignments could have been a bit more detailed.
A strength of the course is that Prof. Gee implemented feedback and listened to the students. A weakness of the course is that it can be fast pace but overall It was a good class.
great intro and overview of stats, great responsive prof, and good working environment

As someone who is interested in the major Psychology, this course was a great way to understand the less conceptual and more real-life aspects of the subject. However, as someone who has never taken a statistics class before, it was a bit fast-paced.
The course is taught well, but there's very little support outside of class.

Strength: We had weekly computer labs as section to learn SPSS.

Weakness: The lab was very rushed, and there was not good retention. I found myself resorting to YouTube tutorials to reteach me how to use SPSS a few times. 

Another Weakness: On the problem set, there were many times when Hakan would count me off for points, and I had no idea why. The other TFs would leave feedback so that I at least knew what I was doing wrong and what I could improve on. But many times, I would get a good chunk counted off- like a whole 5 points off or something like that- always from Hakan, with no feedback whatsoever. Other people in the class mentioned it too, so this was not just my problem either lol.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes definitely, I learned a lot about stats and Dr. Gee was great.

I would definitely recommend this course to another student hoping to gain practical data analysis skills for lab or research settings. SPSS was a totally new software for me and I now feel very comfortable with it. Would recommend as an introductory statistics course and also to people who took AP Stats.

YES! Take it as your QR for Non-STEM! Applied, interesting, and you can do well! Just go to office hours for HWs if needed. Genuienly, Dr. Gee is the fairest QR professor ever (midterm/final exam completely open note, questions released 24 hrs before, she'll change your midterm grade to your final grade if you do better on the final) and INTERESTING!

Yes! This course is extremely well-organized and very well-taught. If you take PSYC 200 with Professor Gee, you will never feel lost/behind/like a course material doesn't match other work you are doing. An excellent course.
It's a great class, and as long as you pay attention to the Lab sections you should be able to do the psets without a ton of difficulty
Yes if you need basic statistics for a major or a QR credit where you want to genuinely learn something.
Yes! I think this is a great QR credit for humanities majors.
Yes, if you are interested in learning about stats from a psychology perspective.
Yes, if you want an intro to stats.
I would definitely recommend this course to any student who wants to take a statistics course but does not have a background in the field.

I would definitely recommend this course as a way to gain a knowledge of statistics without really wanting to know all the details about the math and things like that. If you need to know the practical application of statistics, particularly, though not exclusively, in the field of psychology, this class is excellent. It also was not so challenging that I felt restrained in my learning ability for the sake of the grade. I genuinely felt like I learned things in this course that were built over time with muscle memory. I greatly enjoyed the midterm and final exam formats, which focused more on your ability to apply what you had learned in situations where you would need it in the real world rather than esoteric, non sequitur questions that vaguely tested your knowledge.
Yes, it is a great course for an introduction to statistics.
Yes!!! You learn how to use SPSS and the class is incredibly well-taught.
Yes, I think for any student in psychology, this course not only teaches you statistics, but also the process of conducting research in psychology and many applicable elements to real-world careers.
Nice easy QR that's as interesting as you make it! Very manageable
Sure, if you need it for the psych major
Insightful, makes u think
Yes I would. Although it is required for PSYC majors, I would recommend it to non-Psychology majors who wish to gain an introduction to or stronger grasp of Statistics.
Yes!! Especially to non-stem majors. It is so manageable and fun too.
Yes, very straightforward and good way to become familiar with statistics.

Every student at Yale should take Statistics. It is duly curated to maximize student performance in understanding. Professor Gee has put the utmost time in care into making this course and so have the TFs. The office hours are very accessible, you get tons of feedback on the Psets, and the midterm and final are basically open note and you can prepare for them beforehand. The final project is literally up to you and you can choose to be in a group or work solo. Any pitfall that happened in this course would be up to the student and I wouldn't call it a gut, but it is very attainable and you will not feel stressed in this course at all. As I said before every Yale student should take this course.

YES!!! I learned so much from Prof Gee and the TFs. I now feel like I have a strong base level understanding of how to run statistical tests, which to us and how to analyze the results in a well formatted report. The workload is manageable and the teaching was clear and helpful. I appreciated that every week the answers to the homework and lab assignments were posted a week after students submitted them. This was very helpful for exam reviews.

Definitely. Super engaging way to start out your journey in Statistics. Please take this before senior year if you can, so you can have the statistical grounding to do your senior essay (if you are hoping to get a B.S.!)
Yes. This class was very manageable and is an interesting intro to statistics.
Yes, if you are a psych major this was really good

I would definitely recommend this course to another student who is interested in doing research in psychology or any other type of science. It is super important to be able to make sense of different data and to learn how to design experiments effectively and ethically.
Yes! good foundation to statistics, specifically in the world of psychology. The application of statistics in psychology studies was extremely interesting.
The examples used in fun ; if stats isn't your thing, this class is at least engaging and Prof Gee makes an effort to make sure that the examples and practice problems are all neuro/psych related.
Yes, even if it is not for your major!

Yes! An amazing course especially for students who do not have much background in statistics. As a humanities major I did not think I would be able to be engaged in s course like this, but it was extremely applicable to real-world issues, policy, and advocacy. I especially enjoyed the freedom of the final project.
FOR SURE PLEASE TAKE IT ESPECIALLY IF U LOVE STATS OR PSYCH
If you're interested in gaining a basic understanding of statistics, I would recommend the course! I found it relatively low-stress and I learned a lot.
Yes. This course can introduce students who have completely no knowledge of statistics to learn about it.

Yes, I would recommend this course to another student. The course has taught me invaluable knowledge about statistical skills that will definitely be helpful for me in the future especially in the research field. This course is excellent for anyone seeking a solid foundation in statistics.
Absolutely recommend! The course expectations and requirements were made perfectly clear and the way that the exams were arranged was definitely intended to facilitate student success.
Definitely! Especially if you need a statistics course.
I would recommend this course to other students to learn statistics. It was a great introduction to doing research as well.
Yes!
I absolutely would! This course is a great introduction to statistics, and I thoroughly enjoyed it.
Yes, great teaching staff and clear feedback
Yes because this course isn't very stressful, if you miss a lab or a lecture you can still catch up, and the midterm and final are open note.
I would because Prof. Gee teaches this course very well. I think it is also a good introduction to APA format.
yes, especially if they have not taken stats before in highschool. teaches u good practical skills
Yes, I think it is a fairly doable course that incorporates both aspects of statistical learning and psychological material.
If it's required for your major, yes.  otherwise, take a different stats class.

No. I wish I took a different Statistics (or Data Science) Class to fulfill the stats requirement/prerequisite for the Neuroscience Major. I think I would have preferred learning R instead of learning SPSS, which I found out is a little bit outdated in the neuro field. I would maybe say that this would be a good class to fulfill the Quantitative Reasoning distributional though.
